e read’ on New Year sex assaults","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>JK Rowling has praised the author and poet Musa Okwonga’s response to <a draggable=\"true\" href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/06/tensions-rise-in-germany-over-handling-of-mass-sexual-assaults-in-cologne\">mass sexual assaults in Cologne</a>. Okwonga, who lives in Germany, urges men, “regardless of our ethnic backgrounds, to get genuinely angry about the treatment of women in public spaces”, which Rowling said is the best thing she has read about the sexual assaults in Germany.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/05/germany-crisis-cologne-new-years-eve-sex-attacks\">Cologne inquiry into 'coordinated' New Year's Eve sex attacks</a> </p> </aside>  <p>The attacks took place in Cologne during New Year’s Eve celebrations. Between 500 and 1,000 younger men are said to have been involved in the attacks; around <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jan/06/tensions-rise-in-germany-over-handling-of-mass-sexual-assaults-in-cologne\">100 complaints have been made, two-thirds of which are about sexual assault</a>. The incidents prompted calls for German chancellor Angela Merkel to rethink her open-door policy to refugees.</p> <p>Okwonga, who has won prizes for his poetry, <a href=\"http://www.okwonga.com/how-to-deal-with-the-sexual-assaults-in-cologne/\">writes on his blog</a> that “many of these attackers were already known to the police, and were not drawn from the recently-arrived refugees … [but] that’s not going to stop this conversation being dominated by the issue of race, so we may as well go there”.</p> <p>In an essay, Okwonga goes on to argue that it is more important to focus on a woman’s right not to be assaulted than on race. “As far as being a black man of African descent goes, the racists in Germany and elsewhere hate us anyway,” he writes. The Harry Potter author deemed it “the best comment I’ve read on the Cologne attacks, written by a black man of African descent living in Germany”.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>The cultural expectations of black men in some parts of Germany are already dangerously low</p> <footer> <cite>Musa Okwonga</cite> </footer> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>Okwonga laid out how Germany is “not particularly diverse” racially, that the majority of the black and Arab people who live there are working class, and there is “a tendency, more widespread that many people might like to acknowledge, to regard black men as inherently untrustworthy or criminal”.</p> <p>“In Berlin, where I live, the overwhelming majority of black men you see every day are poor, homeless, or selling drugs by Görlitzer Bahnhof or Warschauer Strasse, two of the city’s busier train stations. And when I say the overwhelming majority, I would say something like 80%, if not more,” he writes.</p> <p>While he loves living in Berlin, Okwonga says some Berliners will leave a space next to him, even on crowded trains, “somehow fearing the prospect of sitting next to a male of African appearance”, and adds: “The cultural expectations of black men in some parts of Germany are already dangerously low.”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jk_rowling/statuses/684831644734369794\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">.<a href=\"https://twitter.com/Okwonga\">@Okwonga</a> Usual character limit problem meant I couldn&#39;t get your name into retweet! Great article. REALLY great. <a href=\"https://t.co/ub3ycti2KP\">https://t.co/ub3ycti2KP</a></p>&mdash; J.K. Rowling (@jk_rowling) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jk_rowling/status/684831644734369794\">January 6, 2016</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <p>Okwonga says the only conclusion to make from this is to “just keep sticking up for the women”.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Why don't we see this as a perfect moment for men to get genuinely angry about the treatment of women?</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>“Here’s what I propose we do. Why don’t we just start with the premise that it is a woman’s fundamental right, wherever she is in the world, to walk the streets and not be groped. And why don’t we see this as a perfect moment for men, regardless of our ethnic backgrounds, to get genuinely angry about the treatment of women in public spaces: to reject with fury the suggestion that we are somehow conditioned by society forever to treat women as objects, condemned by our uncontrollable sexual desires to lunge at them as they walk past.”</p> <p>Okwonga continues: “Let’s do our best to challenge the rampant misogyny, which has gone on worldwide for far too long, and reject whatever lessons of sexist repression we may have been taught. Because women are tired of telling us about this, and exhausted of fighting a battle that for too long has gone overlooked.”</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/football/video/2013/dec/19/musa-okwonga-ode-this-is-football-video\"            data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/3yamv\"                    data-show-ads=\"true\"            data-video-id=\"2015550\"            data-video-name=\"Musa Okwonga's ode to 150 years of the FA: This is Football – video\"            data-video-provider=\"FA\"            data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2013/12/18/1387379066094/Musa-Okwongas-ode-to-150--005.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-425304627\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/poster/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball_8467150.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball.webm\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball/131218ThisIsFootball.m3u8\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2013/12/18/131218ThisIsFootball_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/> </video> <figcaption>Video: Musa Okwonga’s poem This is Football, which was commissioned by the Football Association to commemorate its 150th anniversary.</figcaption> </figure>   <p>Okwonga, who has written two books about football, won the WH Smith young writers’ competition in 1996 and has been commissioned to write poems for the BBC World Service and the Football Association. His essay prompted by the Cologne attacks was <a href=\"http://www.okwonga.com/\">posted on his blog</a> yesterday and has been <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/world/europe/2016/01/how-deal-new-years-eve-sexual-assaults-cologne-and-hamburg\">published by the New Statesman</a>.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fthb","wordcount":"627","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/519bbb1172fb34e92ebaef578dfd7ac0a2090293/0_0_4928_2957/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-14T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Harry Potter author calls response by Musa Okwonga – a writer of African descent living in Germany – ‘the best comment I’ve read’ on New Year sex assaults</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/07/jk-rowling-praises-poet-musa-okwonga-response-cologne-sex-attacks-women","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jan/07/jk-rowling-praises-poet-musa-okwonga-response-cologne-sex-attacks-women","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"519bbb1172fb34e92ebaef578dfd7ac0a2090293","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/519bbb1172fb34e92ebaef578dfd7ac0a2090293/0_0_4928_2957/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"AFP or licensors","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/imag