ollow her on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bakingfiction\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://instagram.com/bakingfiction/\">Instagram</a> at @bakingfiction. ","type":"blog","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/little-library-cafe","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/little-library-cafe","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/series/guardian-books-network","webTitle":"Guardian Books Network","description":"The Guardian Books Network brings you a selection of our favourite literary content from around the world","type":"series","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/guardian-books-network","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/guardian-books-network","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksblog","webTitle":"Books blog","type":"blog","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksblog","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","webTitle":"Food & drink","type":"keyword","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","sectionName":"Life and style","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/recipes","webTitle":"Recipes","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/recipes","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/recipes","references":[]},{"id":"profile/kate-young","webTitle":"Kate Young","r2ContributorId":"72252","firstName":"kate","lastName":"young","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Kate Young writes about her literary and culinary exploits on her blog Little Library Café. Follow @bakingfiction on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bakingfiction\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://instagram.com/bakingfiction/\">Instagram</a></p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/kate-young","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/kate-young","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-07T13:18:05Z","webTitle":"Top 10 terrifying teachers in children’s books","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/07/top-10-terrifying-teachers-in-childrens-books","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"Sophie Cleverly","headline":"Top 10 terrifying teachers in children’s books","trailText":"Got the back to school blues this week? Reassure yourself with the thought that it could be much, much worse…if you had one of these horrible headmasters or ghastly governesses","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>I think all of us can relate to having a terrifying teacher. Whether it’s a no-nonsense Miss that can silence a room with a word, or a bullying Sir that makes you do PE in your socks; every school has one of those teachers that you don’t want to cross. Thankfully, most teachers are brilliant, and don’t lock anybody in cupboards, turn invisible to spy on students, or try to take over the world. But, in this list, we’ll take a look at some of the ones who do...<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/gallery/2013/jun/15/10-best-roald-dahl-characters\">The 10 best Roald Dahl characters – in pictures</a> </p> </aside>  <p> <strong>1. Miss Trunchbull in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/matilda-14.html\">Matilda</a> by Roald Dahl</strong></p> <p>Miss Trunchbull is often the first name to spring to mind when you think of terrifying teachers. In both the book and film of Roald Dahl’s classic, she is an enormous presence in more ways than one. She despises children and strikes fear into the hearts of many readers. Her extreme punishments are famous, including spinning a girl around by her pigtails and forcing a boy who steals a slice of cake to eat an <em>entire</em> cake by himself in front of the school. She runs her school – Crunchem Hall – with an iron fist, and you’d most likely want to avoid being a pupil there at all costs.</p> <p><strong>2. Professor Snape in the <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/harry-potter-and-the-philosopher-s-stone-25.html\">Harry Potter series</a> by JK Rowling</strong></p> <p>Although later revelations in the series changed how some people view Snape, there’s no doubt that he deserves a place on this list. The Hogwarts potions master is a bully, regularly snapping at students and carrying a vendetta against Harry and his friends: <em>“That is the second time you have spoken out of turn, Miss Granger,” said Snape coolly. “Five more points from Gryffindor for being an insufferable know-it-all.”</em> But the raven-haired professor also has links to the dark arts and the notorious Death Eaters, and he isn’t afraid to use an unforgiveable curse...</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/apr/13/jill-murphy-the-worst-witch-sibeal-pounder\">My inspiration: Sibéal Pounder on Jill Murphy's The Worst Witch</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>3. Miss Hardbroom in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/worst-witch-4.html\">The Worst Witch series</a> by Jill Murphy</strong></p> <p>Much like Snape is to Dumbledore, potions teacher Miss Hardbroom is the super strict counterpart to the kindly headmistress Miss Cackle. With her black dress, sharp face and hair in an impossibly tight bun, Miss Hardbroom would likely get on well with Miss Fox in my books, and would probably share her views on discipline. She is frequently displeased with main character Mildred Hubble, and indeed it is her who brands Mildred with the title of <em>“the worst witch in the school”</em>. Miss Hardbroom is a very powerful witch, and even possesses the ability to become invisible and spy on pupils – every mischievous student’s worst nightmare. She does have a softer side, though, which occasionally shines through when Mildred manages to save the day.</p> <p><strong>4. The Demon Headmaster in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/demon-headmaster-2.html\">The Demon Headmaster series</a> by Gillian Cross</strong></p> <p>The Demon Headmaster was terrifying to me as a kid. Whether it was the TV show or Cross’s books, you couldn’t escape those glowing green eyes, the dark glasses, the deadly stare. With his hypnotic powers, he controls an army of prefects – only shy new pupil Dinah Glass and secret club SPLAT are immune. He has ambitions beyond just controlling his school, too, using his abilities to try and take over the world in later books. Little is known about the man himself, not even his name, which makes him all the more mysterious and creepy.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/oct/31/jk-rowling-reveals-the-secrets-of-dolores-umbridge\">JK Rowling reveals the secrets of Dolores Umbridge</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>5. Professor Umbridge in the <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/harry-potter-and-the-philosopher-s-stone-25.html\">Harry Potter series</a> by JK Rowling</strong></p> <p>Few characters are more despised by readers than Dolores Umbridge. The pink-clad and kitten-mad Defence Against The Dark Arts professor starts off as merely sickly smug and annoying, before quickly taking a darker turn. She refuses to believe that the evil Lord Voldemort has returned, instead branding Harry Potter as attention seeking. She forces him to write lines of <em>“I must not tell lies”</em> – but they’re no ordinary lines, as he must use a Blood Quill which carves the words into his hand.</p> <p>In her time at Hogwarts, Umbridge picks on both students and staff, has beloved teachers fired, and refuses to properly teach her subject. She proves to be highly prejudiced against “muggle borns” (wizards born to non-magical parents), which leads her to committing atrocities later in the series. Umbridge is a good lesson in not judging by appearances, and is truly a terrifying teacher in more ways than one.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/sep/27/top-10-villains-in-ya-fiction\">Top 10 villains in YA fiction</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>6. Miss Vole in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/308491/\">Moondial</a> by Helen Cresswell</strong></p> <p>Miss Vole is another character who frightened me when I was younger. In the book<em>, </em>young Minty discovers that the sundial in the gardens of the nearby Belton House is in fact a moondial, a magical object that can transport you forwards and backwards in time. In the 18<sup>th</sup> century, a girl named Sarah is tormented by Miss Vole – a wicked governess (a live-in teacher) who convinces her that her birthmark is a sign of evil. She tells her that if she ever looks in the mirror, the mirror will crack and the devil will come out to get her. Although we only see glimpses of Miss Vole, she was always such a vivid character that she stuck in my imagination. Unlike poor Sarah, Minty can escape by returning to the present. That is until the mysterious Miss Raven arrives at Minty’s aunt’s home, and her face is very familiar…</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2011/sep/14/little-princess-hodgson-burnett-review\">A Little Princess by Frances Hodgson Burnett - review</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>7. Miss Minchin in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/little-princess-10.html\">A Little Princess</a> by Frances Hodgson Burnett</strong></p> <p>Continuing the tradition of scary adults abusing their power over children is Frances Hodgson Burnett’s Miss Minchin. When seven-year-old Sara Crewe joins her boarding school, she hides her jealousy over the girl’s wealth and popularity. But when Sara’s father tragically dies and can no longer pay the bills, the horrible headmistress has her imprisoned in the attic with little but a few dresses and a doll, and forces her to work as a scullery maid. </p> <p>Throughout all the abuse Sara gets from the headmistress, she remains polite and dignified – just like a real princess. <em>“If I am a princess in rags and tatters,”</em> she says, <em>“I can be a princess inside. It would be easy to be a princess if I were dressed in cloth of gold, but it is a great deal more of a triumph to be one all the time when no one knows it.”</em></p> <p><strong>8. Miss Slighcarp and Mrs Brisket in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/wolves-of-willoughby-chase.html\">The Wolves of Willoughby Chase</a> by Joan Aiken</strong></p> <p>For this entry, we have a dastardly duo of terrifying teachers. In a time that never really happened, England has been overrun by wolves in a cold winter. A young girl named Sylvia is sent to live with her cousin Bonnie in the grand Willoughby Estate, only to find that her kindly parents are off on a trip and are leaving the intimidating Miss Slighcarp in charge of the girls. The sharp woman is immediately bad-tempered, striking Bonnie and locking her in a cupboard. She steals Bonnie’s mother’s dresses, fires all of the other household staff and threatens to starve the children. Eventually, when the full extent of her devious plans are revealed, the girls are shipped off to a horrific boarding school. There they meet horrible headmistress Mrs Brisket, who is just as bad (if not worse): she forces her pupils to work as slaves in terrible conditions while she lives in luxury. Truly a nasty double act you wouldn’t want to meet.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/oct/29/top-10-haunted-houses-in-fiction\">Top 10 haunted houses in fiction</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>9. Miss Lupescu in <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/graveyard-book-2.html\">The Graveyard Book</a> by Neil Gaiman</strong></p> <p>Miss Lupescu is a terrifying teacher in a few strange and unexpected ways. When she’s first set the task of looking after Bod, a child raised in the graveyard, she is strict and seems lacking in empathy. She feeds him strange, horrible foods that make him sick: <em>“dumplings swimming in lard; thick reddish purple soup with a lump of sour cream in it; cold boiled potatoes; cold garlic-heavy sausages.”</em> She demands that he pays attention to her boring lessons. Only later on in the book when Bod falls into deep trouble with a group of ghouls do we find that these lessons were very important indeed. Miss Lupescu is much more than she seems, and she becomes an important guardian, protector and friend for Bod.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2014/jul/10/terry-pratchett-interview-dragons-at-crumbling-castle\">Terry Pratchett: I started writing my new book when I was 17-years-old</a> </p> </aside>  <p><strong>10. Susan Sto Helit in the <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/first-discworld-novels.html\">Discworld series</a> by Terry Pratchett</strong></p> <p>When your teacher is the granddaughter of Death himself, you know not to cross her. Although not usually terrifying to her students (unless they misbehave), Susan certainly strikes fear into the heart of any monsters that might seek to harm them. In her first job as a governess, she handily dispatches anything that might be lurking under the bed with the help of a poker. She’s respected, feared, and loved, but certainly is no Mary Poppins. In fact she swears that if she ever finds herself dancing on rooftops with chimney sweeps, she’ll beat herself to death with her own umbrella.</p> <p>When Susan graduates to school teaching, she uses her powers to give the children some fascinating lessons: whether it’s viewing ancient battles first-hand, or meeting Death and his horse. Her teaching methods are somewhat unusual, with parents and other teachers claiming that the tasks she sets are far too hard for children – to which Susan responds that she hasn’t told the children this, and so far they haven’t noticed. She is greatly fond of children, as long as they aren’t raw…</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"a8aab72a1a568c13212a61f2bd22df12602b1e1d\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/a8aab72a1a568c13212a61f2bd22df12602b1e1d/0_0_4000_2399/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Sophie Cleverly\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Sophie Cleverly.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Sophie Cleverly is the author of the <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/lost-twin.html\">Scarlet and Ivy series</a> of mystery adventures set in a boarding school. The latest book is <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/346061/\">The Whispers in the Walls</a>. You can find out more about Sophie and her books at <a href=\"http://www.hapfairy.co.uk/\">www.hapfairy.co.uk</a> or follow Sophie on twitter @hapfairy</p>