/neilgaiman","webTitle":"Neil Gaiman","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/neilgaiman","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/neilgaiman","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-07T13:05:05Z","webTitle":"#DiverseDecember creators expand 'hugely popular' social media campaign to run for all of 2016","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/jan/07/diverse-december-creators-expand-social-media-campaign-readdiverse2016","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Alison Flood","headline":"#DiverseDecember creators expand 'hugely popular' social media campaign to run for all of 2016","trailText":"The original hashtag, created after the World Book Night failed to include BAME authors on its giveaway list, has rebranded as #ReadDiverse2016 to ‘celebrate diversity in all its forms’ for the whole year","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>#DiverseDecember, last month’s celebration of writers of colour, was “hugely popular” according to the book bloggers who created it, and who are planning to continue the initiative through 2016.</p> <p>Bloggers Naomi Frisby and Dan Lipscombe launched the #DiverseDecember campaign on Twitter, in response to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/25/world-book-night-criticised-all-white-2016-giveaway-list\">absence of titles by writers of colour on the books selected for this year’s World Book Night</a>. “The idea was to only read books by BAME writers throughout December, tweeting titles and mini-reviews to highlight books and share recommendations by a range of voices,” said Frisby, who blogs at <a href=\"https://thewritesofwoman.wordpress.com/\">the Writes of Women</a>. “It’s been hugely popular. More people than we ever envisaged have taken part.”</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/dec/11/how-do-we-stop-uk-publishing-being-so-posh-white-male\">How do we stop UK publishing being so posh and white?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>“When I coined the term, I did so in order to celebrate different voices in literature – I didn’t think it would take off the way it has,” added Lipscombe, who blogs at <a href=\"https://utterbiblio.wordpress.com/\">UtterBiblio</a>. “I’ve seen many more people talking about diversity over the last few weeks, the publishing industry needs to take note.”</p> <p>Publishers as well as readers and authors got involved in the project, said Frisby, with both mainstream and independent presses posting recommended reads and running giveaways. “Statistics suggest we reached more than 13,500 people via the <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ReadDiverse2016?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw\">Diverse December Twitter account</a> and the <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/diversedecember?src=hash\">Diverse December hashtag</a> trended for five hours on 1 December and 17 hours on the 2nd,” she said.</p> <p>Frisby believes the campaign has helped to introduce readers to writers and books they might not otherwise have heard of. “It’s been interesting to see some readers talk about how they’ve never interrogated their reading choices before, and are now reading a narrow range of voices because of this. It was great to see some publishers taking part,” she says, adding that she hopes that as people read and discuss work by writers of colour, publishing catalogues and the industry itself will become more diverse.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/30/authors-slam-lack-diversity-in-uk-publishing-nikesh-shukla-jon-mcgregor\">'Where are the brown people?': authors slam lack of diversity in UK publishing</a> </p> </aside>  <p>With the project’s success, Lipscombe and Frisby have expanded the campaign to a whole year, rebranding it as <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ReadDiverse2016\">#ReadDiverse2016</a>. “We’re still celebrating and recommending writers of colour, but also writers who identify as part of the LGBT communities and those who are differently abled,” said Frisby. “We’re celebrating diversity in all its forms, hoping to reach a point where someone’s race, sexual preference or body no longer marks them as ‘other’ and no longer forms a barrier to people publishing the stories they want to tell.”</p> <p>The author Nikesh Shukla, who <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/30/authors-slam-lack-diversity-in-uk-publishing-nikesh-shukla-jon-mcgregor\">first highlighted World Book Night’s lack of diversity</a>, said: “Various microaggressions that people have experienced in isolation are now being talked about on social media. And the conversation is widening to look at equally important things like class,” said Shukla, who is editing an anthology on race and immigration by British black, Asian, and minority ethnic (BAME) writers.</p> <p>However, after scanning lists of titles to be published in 2016, Shukla says there was still a “lack of books by people of colour”. He has put together <a href=\"http://mediadiversified.org/2015/12/20/12-writers-of-colour-im-excited-about-reading-in-2016/\">a selection for Media Diversified</a>, after asking publishers for suggestions. “About 40 to 50 books were recommended to me,” he says. “Hardly any of them were by British writers of colour, and of those that were, hardly any were debuts. Which made me slightly unnerved about the lack of nurturing of homegrown talent.” </p> <p>Shukla has been contacted by almost 100 BAME writers since he offered to help ones those looking for representation. “Out of the 100 or so enquiries I’ve had, two now have representation, and half have been sent to different agents. The rest, I’ve sent out advice on how to get the book ready for submission, or the manuscripts are still being worked on,” he said.</p> <h2>Recommended reads from Naomi Frisby and Dan Lipscombe, following #DiverseDecember</h2> <ol> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/oct/08/between-the-world-and-me-sukhdev-sandhu-review\">Between the World and Me</a> by Ta-Nehisi Coates<br /></li> <li>Trumpet by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/apr/27/life-writing-jackie-kay\">Jackie Kay</a><br /></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/jul/26/thirst-by-kerry-hudson-review-working-class-heroes\">Thirst</a> by Kerry Hudson<br /></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/sep/26/all-of-the-above-james-dawson-review\">All of the Above</a> by Juno Dawson<br /></li> <li>Kindred by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/apr/30/unseen-octavia-e-butler-stories-recovered-science-fiction\">Octavia Butler</a><br /></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jan/20/brief-wondrous-life-of-oscar-wao-novel-21st-century-best-junot-diaz\">The Brief Wondrous Life of Oscar Wao</a> by Junot Díaz</li> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/jun/19/the-year-of-the-runaways-sunjeev-sahota-review-political-novel\">The Year of the Runaways</a> by Sunjeev Sahota<br /></li> <li>The Private Life of Mrs Sharma by Ratika Kapur<br /></li> <li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/apr/25/maggie-me-damian-barr-review\">Maggie &amp; Me</a> by Damian Barr<br /></li> <li>Go Tell It on the Mountain by <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/sep/14/jamesbaldwin\">James Baldwin</a><br /></li> </ol>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fgpf","wordcount":"700","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/bde050ba035a6ed9ec2d249740cb05362e417eb9/0_307_2003_1202/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-14T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>The original hashtag, 