eguardian.com/world/lgbt-rights","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/lgbt-rights","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"profile/alisonflood","webTitle":"Alison Flood","r2ContributorId":"27440","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/3/14/1300117336779/Alison.jpg","firstName":"","lastName":"flood","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Alison Flood is a writer on guardian.co.uk/books and former news editor of the Bookseller</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/alisonflood","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/alisonflood","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-07T13:03:18Z","webTitle":"Ebook authors may be an endangered species – but we can fight back | David Boyle","sectionId":"commentisfree","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"commentisfree/2016/jan/07/ebook-writers-society-of-authors-amazon","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"David Boyle","headline":"Ebook authors may be an endangered species – but we can fight back\r\n","trailText":"The Society of Authors has warned of the abysmal pay received by many writers. Yet with innovation – and the book-buying public’s support – we may yet survive","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>‘Yes, I’m a writer; would you like a copy of my book? Would you like me to sign it for you? No trouble; it would be an honour. Oh, hold on, I can’t – it’s an <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/ebooks\" title=\"\">ebook</a>.” This is one of the disadvantages of writing ebooks, rather than the good old-fashioned tomes that gather dust. In fact, ebooks are so shiny that they don’t actually exist in the physical world.</p> <p>You worry a little, <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/-/e/B000APQC2K/ref=dp_byline_sr_ebooks_1?ie=UTF8&amp;text=David+Boyle&amp;search-alias=digital-text&amp;field-author=David+Boyle&amp;sort=relevancerank\" title=\"\">as an ebook author</a>, that people might be sceptical that you have ever written anything. Or indeed whether all that writing exists in any real sense, since you can’t see it on your shelf. I mean, where is it? You can’t lend it, copy it or give it as a present. Yet bizarrely, online pirates seem capable of giving it away for free within days of it going on sale.</p> <p>There are certainly advantages to writing the new generation of ebooks that are designed as such, rather than as reluctantly issued e-versions of printed books. They are often a convenient length – maybe a fifth or quarter as long as a traditional book, just long enough to read on a transatlantic flight or a train to Scotland. And they are priced low enough to sell widely. It is a marginal decision to buy a short book at £1.99 or £2.99. You might as well buy it as not.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/dec/27/new-literature-on-way\">Print survives as a new literature is born | Robert McCrum</a> </p> </aside>  <p>They have, in that respect, breathed an innovative energy into the book market, with low-cost ebooks at one end and real books, published as objects of beauty, at the other. It’s created another squeezed middle: what is disappearing are the cheap, ubiquitous throwaway paperbacks that fell apart after one reading.</p> <p>As an ebook writer, I’m only too aware of the problem flagged up by the Society of Authors, that <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/12083511/Authors-could-become-an-endangered-species-thanks-to-e-book-deals.html\" title=\"\">the income of writers is still falling</a>. I certainly agree that authors should get at least half the royalties on ebooks; the big publishers often fob them off with 25% or less. Well, I would say that.</p> <p>Yet this is not primarily a difficulty with ebooks. It is a symptom of two more fundamental, linked problems. The competition watchdogs have allowed <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/amazon\" title=\"\">Amazon</a> and the big supermarkets to strangle what had been a working business model. As a result, the remaining, desperately consolidated, mainstream publishers are trapped in a business model that works for nobody – except perhaps for the 5%, the mega-earning authors, who take 43% of all the money.</p> <p>The Society is absolutely right that the nation lives by its creativity, and we are worse off financially and, dare I say, spiritually, if authors have to spend most of their time working in financial services to eke out an evening writing a book.</p> <p>Something has to happen. I can’t imagine that we will return any time soon to the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2010/jun/17/net-book-agreement-publishing\" title=\"\">net book agreement</a>, when guaranteed prices kept the midlist authors afloat. Nor are the regulators going to do what they ought to, and break up the budding online monopolies such as Amazon. As a result, the pressures on the old publishers are going to remain intense – though not so intense that they can’t offer better terms to their authors on ebook sales.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Regulators have to keep an eye on the bookselling monopolies, which could snuff us innovators out in the blink of an eye</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>So what can authors do? They can be a bit bolshie when they are asked to speak for no fee. They can refuse to buy any book that costs less than a cup of coffee (except when it’s on special offer, perhaps). And they can innovate their hearts out.</p> <p>There is already huge innovation in the book market, but very little in how the poor authors are paid. But strangely enough, it is the specialist ebook publishers who are developing a different model that pays authors 40 or 50% (of not much, it is true).</p> <p>That is why I’m going to carry on writing ebooks. The length suits me, and I believe it suits my readers. And – although Amazon’s grip on the market prevents us from starting print publishing imprints (60% of a physical book’s price goes to them) – it doesn’t stop us starting our own e-publishing imprints.</p> <p>In fact, that’s exactly what I have decided to do – I’ve published only <a href=\"http://www.amazon.co.uk/Scandal-How-homosexuality-became-crime-ebook/dp/B019EN86XQ/ref=sr_1_1_twi_kin_2?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1452120949&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=boyle+scandal\" title=\"\">one book</a> so far, but there is a heady whiff of independence about the idea. And I can pay my authors an encouragingly fair percentage too (70%).</p> <p>But it does rely on two things. First, regulators have to keep an eye on the bookselling monopolies, which could snuff us innovators out in the blink of an eye. Second, the book-buying public has to consciously innovate too – where and how it buys, and maybe even what it buys too. But don’t let’s blame ebooks. They may even be part of the solution.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ftm8","wordcount":"805","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/29ac249477e7cbab5444e7ed86300dfc30746580/0_0_4000_2400/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-10T13:03:18Z","standfirst":"The Society of Authors has warned of the abysmal pay received by many writers. Yet with innovation – and the book-buying public’s support – we may yet survive"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jan/07/ebook-writers-society-of-authors-amazon","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2016/jan/07/ebook-writers-society-of-authors-amazon","sectio